<figureCitation box="[794,823,1481,1505]" captionStart="Figs 82–99" captionStartId="53.[151,191,2018,2040]" captionTargetBox="[151,1398,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-116@53.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="Figs 82–99: Abdomen of Zyras spp.: pindarae (82–85), perforatus (86), championi (87), pallipes (88), longilobatus (89), hastatus (90), truncatus (91), latilobatus (92), morvani (93), condignus (94), hirtus (95), gardneri (96), hirsutiventris (97), parageminus (98), alternans (99). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742383/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">97</figureCitation>
): forebody black; abdomen blackish-brown to black; legs dark-yellowish, with the profemora dark-brown and the apical two-fifths or the apical halves of the meso- and metafemora blackish; antennae blackish, with the basal three antennomeres dark-brown; maxillary palpi darkbrown with palpomere IV yellowish.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[794,1399,1417,2081]" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">
Head (
<figureCitation box="[875,949,1673,1697]" captionStart="Figs 55–67" captionStartId="49.[151,191,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[151,1397,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-119@49.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figs 55–67: Forebody of Zyrasspp.:parageminus (55–56; 55:holotype;56:holotype ofZ. nameriensis),latilobatus (57),alternans (58), hirtus (59), nilgiriensis (60), russiceps (61), gardneri (62), hirsutiventris (63),luteipes (64), proximus, holotype (65), brignolii, holotype of Z. thainiger (66), novinversus (67). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742375" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742375/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Fig. 63</figureCitation>
) distinctly transverse, median portion extensively impunctate; punctures in lateral portions moderately sparse and moderately coarse. Eyes longer than postocular region in dorsal view. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[1316,1391,1769,1793]" captionStart="Figs 1–41" captionStartId="45.[151,191,1956,1978]" captionTargetBox="[152,1389,232,1855]" captionTargetId="figure-203@45.[151,1398,232,1874]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="Figs 1–41:Antennae of Zyrasspp.:kraatzi(1),exasperatus(2),pindarae (3–5),perforatus(6),championi(7),pallipes (8),condignus (9), nitens (10), truncatus (11), nilgiriensis (12), hirsutiventris (13), russiceps (14), brignolii (15), hastatus (16), parageminus (17–18), latilobatus (19), alternans (20), hirtus (21), nigroaeneus (22), luteipes (23), longilobatus (24), morvani (25), gratellus (Malaysia) (26), castaneus, lectotype (27),proximus (28–29),novinversus (30–31), brevilobatus(32), parvicollis(33), ambulans (34),matangensis (35), densissimus (36), densihirtus (37), nigrihirtus (38), gratellus (Sulawesi) (39), gardneri (40), titan (41). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742367" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742367/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Fig. 13</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[794,921,1801,1825]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.3" metricValueMax="2.5" metricValueMin="2.1" pageId="27" pageNumber="144" unit="mm" value="2.3" valueMax="2.5" valueMin="2.1">2.1–2.5 mm</quantity>
long and rather slender; antennomeres IV oblong or as long as broad, V–VI approximately as long as broad or weakly transverse, VII–X of increasing width and increasingly transverse, X approximately 1.5 times as broad as long, and XI of distinctly conical shape, short, much shorter than the combined length of IX and X.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="27.[794,1399,1417,2081]" lastBlockId="28.[189,795,233,1121]" lastPageId="28" lastPageNumber="145" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">
Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[917,992,1993,2017]" captionStart="Figs 55–67" captionStartId="49.[151,191,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[151,1397,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-119@49.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figs 55–67: Forebody of Zyrasspp.:parageminus (55–56; 55:holotype;56:holotype ofZ. nameriensis),latilobatus (57),alternans (58), hirtus (59), nilgiriensis (60), russiceps (61), gardneri (62), hirsutiventris (63),luteipes (64), proximus, holotype (65), brignolii, holotype of Z. thainiger (66), novinversus (67). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742375" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742375/files/figure.png" pageId="27" pageNumber="144">Fig. 63</figureCitation>
) approximately 1.15 times as broad as long and approximately 1.3 times as broad as head, broadest in anterior half; lateral margins distinctly sinuate in posterior half in dorsal view; punctation rather fine and dense, regularly distributed; midline narrowly impunctate; pubescence brown, long, and sub-erect to erect.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[189,795,233,1121]" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">
Elytra (
<figureCitation box="[266,341,329,353]" captionStart="Figs 55–67" captionStartId="49.[151,191,1991,2013]" captionTargetBox="[151,1397,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-119@49.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="49" captionText="Figs 55–67: Forebody of Zyrasspp.:parageminus (55–56; 55:holotype;56:holotype ofZ. nameriensis),latilobatus (57),alternans (58), hirtus (59), nilgiriensis (60), russiceps (61), gardneri (62), hirsutiventris (63),luteipes (64), proximus, holotype (65), brignolii, holotype of Z. thainiger (66), novinversus (67). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742375" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742375/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Fig. 63</figureCitation>
) approximately 0.9 times as long as pronotum; punctation dense and fine, only slightly less dense posteriorly than anteriorly; whole disc with dense and sub-erect brown pubescence. Hind wings fully developed. Metatarsomere I nearly as long as the combined length of II–IV.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[189,795,233,1121]" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">
Abdomen (
<figureCitation box="[317,392,521,545]" captionStart="Figs 82–99" captionStartId="53.[151,191,2018,2040]" captionTargetBox="[151,1398,232,1962]" captionTargetId="figure-116@53.[151,1398,232,1971]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="Figs 82–99: Abdomen of Zyras spp.: pindarae (82–85), perforatus (86), championi (87), pallipes (88), longilobatus (89), hastatus (90), truncatus (91), latilobatus (92), morvani (93), condignus (94), hirtus (95), gardneri (96), hirsutiventris (97), parageminus (98), alternans (99). Scale bar: 1.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742383" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742383/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Fig. 97</figureCitation>
) approximately as broad as elytra, with moderately deep anterior impressions on tergites III–V; anterior impressions of tergites III–V each with a transverse row of shallow and indistinct grooves (not punctation); tergites III–V each with two transverse rows of rather numerous setiferous punctures posteriorly; tergite VI with extensive non-setiferous puncturation in anterior half, with micropunctation and with scattered setiferous punctures in posterior half; tergite VII with non-setiferous punctation in anterior half and with setiferous punctation not arranged in distinct rows in posterior half, posterior margin with palisade fringe; tergite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[336,423,905,929]" captionStart="Figs 174–190" captionStartId="58.[189,229,2020,2042]" captionTargetBox="[190,1430,246,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-107@58.[189,1436,237,1976]" captionText="Figs 174–190: Zyras gardneri (174–177), Z. hirsutiventris (178–181), Z. luteipes (182–186), and Z. russiceps (187–190): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (174–175, 178–179, 182–183, 187–188); male tergite VIII (176, 180, 185, 189); male sternite VIII (177, 181, 186, 190); paramere (184). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888372" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888372/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Fig. 180</figureCitation>
) with moderately dense punctation everywhere, except near anterior margin, posterior margin shallowly concave in the middle; all sternites with long brown pubescence posteriorly.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[189,795,233,1121]" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">
♂: sternite VIII (
<figureCitation box="[382,469,1033,1057]" captionStart="Figs 174–190" captionStartId="58.[189,229,2020,2042]" captionTargetBox="[190,1430,246,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-107@58.[189,1436,237,1976]" captionText="Figs 174–190: Zyras gardneri (174–177), Z. hirsutiventris (178–181), Z. luteipes (182–186), and Z. russiceps (187–190): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (174–175, 178–179, 182–183, 187–188); male tergite VIII (176, 180, 185, 189); male sternite VIII (177, 181, 186, 190); paramere (184). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888372" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888372/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Fig. 181</figureCitation>
) strongly convex posteriorly; median lobe of aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[480,624,1065,1089]" captionStart="Figs 174–190" captionStartId="58.[189,229,2020,2042]" captionTargetBox="[190,1430,246,1968]" captionTargetId="figure-107@58.[189,1436,237,1976]" captionText="Figs 174–190: Zyras gardneri (174–177), Z. hirsutiventris (178–181), Z. luteipes (182–186), and Z. russiceps (187–190): median lobe of aedeagus in lateral and in ventral view (174–175, 178–179, 182–183, 187–188); male tergite VIII (176, 180, 185, 189); male sternite VIII (177, 181, 186, 190); paramere (184). Scale bars: 0.5 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5888372" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5888372/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Figs 178–179</figureCitation>
) 
<quantity box="[641,794,1065,1089]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.049999999999999" metricValueMax="8.299999999999999" metricValueMin="7.800000000000001" pageId="28" pageNumber="145" unit="mm" value="0.8049999999999999" valueMax="0.83" valueMin="0.78">0.78–0.83 mm</quantity>
long; paramere 
<quantity box="[355,449,1097,1121]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.7" pageId="28" pageNumber="145" unit="mm" value="0.87">0.87 mm</quantity>
long and with short apical lobe.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[189,794,1161,1601]" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,396,1161,1185]" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Comparative notes</emphasis>
: Like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1939" box="[459,575,1161,1185]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gardneri">
<emphasis box="[459,575,1161,1185]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Z. gardneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, this species belongs to the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="KRAATZ" baseAuthorityYear="1859" box="[266,357,1193,1217]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirtus">
<emphasis box="[266,357,1193,1217]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Z. hirtus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. It is readily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cameron" authorityYear="1939" box="[189,305,1225,1249]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gardneri">
<emphasis box="[189,305,1225,1249]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Z. gardneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the different coloration of the antennae, the elytra, the abdomen, and the legs, by less slender antennae with distinctly more transverse preapical antennomeres, as well as by the different punctation pattern of the abdomen. Regarding the shape of the ventral process of the aedeagus, 
<taxonomicName box="[381,547,1385,1409]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Myrmedonia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hirsutiventris">
<emphasis box="[381,547,1385,1409]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Z. hirsutiventris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="ASSING, 2016" authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2016" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flexus">
<emphasis box="[704,793,1385,1409]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Z. flexus</emphasis>
ASSING, 2016
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[399,467,1417,1441]" country="China" name="Fujian" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Fujian</collectingRegion>
(
<collectingCountry box="[482,552,1417,1441]" name="China" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">China</collectingCountry>
), from which it differs by darker coloration of the whole body (including the legs and antennae) and the larger aedeagus (
<taxonomicName authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2016" box="[623,712,1481,1505]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flexus">
<emphasis box="[623,712,1481,1505]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Z. flexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: length of median lobe 
<quantity box="[369,452,1513,1537]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" pageId="28" pageNumber="145" unit="mm" value="0.7">0.7 mm</quantity>
) with an apically less strongly angled ventral process (lateral view). For illustrations of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="ASSING" authorityYear="2016" box="[189,278,1577,1601]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Zyras" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="28" pageNumber="145" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flexus">
<emphasis box="[189,278,1577,1601]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Z. flexus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
see 
<bibRefCitation author="ASSING, V." box="[323,492,1577,1601]" pageId="28" pageNumber="145" pagination="87 - 175" refId="ref57174" refString="ASSING, V. 2016 a: A revision of Zyras STEPHENS sensu strictu of China, Taiwan, and Hong Kong, with records and (re-) descriptions of some species from other regions (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae: Lomechusini). - Stuttgarter Beitrage zur Naturkunde A, Neue Serie 9: 87 - 175." type="journal article" year="2016">ASSING (2016a)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="145" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="28.[189,794,1641,1825]" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,549,1641,1665]" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Distribution and natural history</emphasis>
: The currently known distribution is confined to three localities in North 
<collectingCountry box="[738,794,1673,1697]" name="India" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">India</collectingCountry>
(
<collectingRegion box="[196,336,1705,1729]" country="India" name="Uttarakhand" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Uttarakhand</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[352,425,1705,1729]" country="India" name="Assam" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Assam</collectingRegion>
) and 
<collectingCountry box="[497,560,1705,1729]" name="Nepal" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Nepal</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[580,652,1705,1729]" captionStart="Map 7" captionStartId="67.[151,196,1246,1267]" captionTargetBox="[351,1198,232,1238]" captionTargetId="figure-79@67.[351,1198,232,1238]" captionTargetPageId="67" captionText="Map 7: Revised distributions of Zyras gardneri (black circles), Z. hirsutiventris (white diamonds), Z. parageminus (black triangles), Z. hastatus (white triangle), Z. hirtus (white circles), and Z. latilobatus (star) in India and adjacent regions." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5742413" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5742413/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Map 7</figureCitation>
). The above male from East 
<collectingCountry box="[377,440,1737,1761]" name="Nepal" pageId="28" pageNumber="145">Nepal</collectingCountry>
was already reported by 
<bibRefCitation author="PACE, R." pageId="28" pageNumber="145" pagination="125 - 145" refId="ref58393" refString="PACE, R. 1992: Aleocharinae nepalesi del Museo di Ginevra. Parte VI: Myrmedoniini (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae). - Revue Suisse de Zoologie 99 (1): 125 - 145." type="journal article" year="1992">PACE (1992)</bibRefCitation>
. The altitudes range from 150 to approximately 
<quantity box="[189,270,1801,1825]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.55" pageId="28" pageNumber="145" unit="m" value="1550.0">1550 m</quantity>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
